Meet the girls of @saltleywfc, a Birmingham-based women's football team inspiring young women of all abilities and backgrounds to participate in outdoor sports ğŸ™Œ

Saltley Stallions Women's FC, CO-founded by @obayedhussain and @yas.nessa, is a community encouraging women to get involved in recreational football sessions. Set up in 2019 with just 4 players, the team now has over 200 women and girls who take part in open access football sessions and regular five a side leagues. They've since renovated a shipping container into an on-site gym to support the team's training.

With South Asian participation in sports often being overlooked, it is @obayedhussain and @yas.nessaâ€™s goal to ensure Saltley Stallions Women's FC is a community available for everyone of all abilities to inspire many generations to come.

We asked Muslim members of the Gymshark family to share stories of what Ramadan means to them, their communities and their fitness journeys. Here's how @realrubaali commits to their faith and training throughout this month...

Ramadan to me is a month of purification, heightened devotion and self-reflection. Itâ€™s truly a cleanse for the mind, body and soul.

Some might see Ramadan as a â€œsetbackâ€ for their fitness goals - but I see it otherwise. I see it as a challenge to push my body and mind to go beyond its own limits.

Itâ€™s remarkable how much the body is capable of when the mind is the commander. Over the years, Iâ€™ve trained my mind to understand that itâ€™s all mental. I donâ€™t take shortcuts just because Iâ€™m fasting. Whether my body is fed or not, I show up every day with effort and determination to be better. Itâ€™s all about adapting to your circumstances and finding what works best for you.

During Ramadan I gain far more willpower than any other month of the year. For my brothers and sisters who are preparing for Ramadan, remember that with sacrifice comes success. With hardship comes ease. And with determination you can gain the benefits of Ramadan while improving your fitness. Stay strong, always.

-
I started bodybuilding because I was very skinny and insecure. I wanted to look and feel more masculine about myself. I am a transgender man, but I never allowed that to define who I was or my capabilities.

After training for some time, I was able to start training at Bev Francis Powerhouse gym, where I was able to meet many incredible athletes who inspired me to see how far I could push my body and mind.
After following a strict training and dieting regime I put on a large amount of muscle mass in a considerably short amount of time, where then I decided to compete in my first bodybuilding show.

After 21 weeks of a gruelling bodybuilding prep, I went on to win Teen Classic Physique and place Second in the Junior Novice Division at my first show.
